Ah, I see.  I had traced through the actual code of eTaskGetState(), and it looks like it is safe, but it's probably better to follow the FreeRTOS rules.

One option might be to block for a short time until just before startRoutine() calls entry->start_routine(), and rely on the beginning of startRoutine() to set the PID and thread_id fields.  I think you should unconditionally return the thread ID rather than setting *thread = 0 if it is deleted quickly.

Something like this:

    static void *startRoutine(void *arg)
    {
        ...

        entry->pid = xGetCurrentTaskPid();
        entry->thread_id = xTaskGetCurrentTaskHandle();

        indicateThreadInitialized();
        ...

    ...
    ret = xTaskCreate((TaskFunction_t)startRoutine,name,stack_size,(void*)entry,prio,&temp);
    if (ret == pdPASS)
    {
        *thread = (pthread_t) temp;
        waitForThreadToInitialize();
        ret = 0;
    }
    ...

